Global tranformation of features¶

In [5]:
# in order to plot age (@time of the event!) instead of year of birth
full_df.Year = full_df.RaceYear - full_df.Year

# Round `Distance` feature:
full_df.Distance = full_df.Distance.round()
full_df.Distance = full_df.Distance.astype('int')

# transform timedelta in minutes!
full_df.Time = full_df.Time.astype('timedelta64[m]')

# transform Pace timedelta in sec!  - here is better to keep lower resolution!
full_df.Pace = full_df.Pace.astype('timedelta64[s]')

# these 2 are actually the same event!
full_df.Race = full_df.Race.apply(
    lambda x: 'Lucerne Marathon, Luzern' if x == 'SwissCityMarathon - Lucerne, Luzern' else x
)

Note on unique runners¶

Mind that the number of runners is less than # rows, due to namesakes, there are born in different time, or live in different place.

Checking the demographics of few races, we could notice that there are still some namesakes born in the same date. One way to detected them is to check full_df.LivingPlace, within the same race.
However this method is not always reliable, as some people change residence during their running career - we could found that, by cross-checking our dataset with other resources on the web.
We therefore decided to keep only the unique name - birthday tuples (full_df.UserID computed previously in the 'parsing step')

Conclusions¶

It's not possible to claim a global trend for the runners' mean age, across time.
In few events we observe a clear decrease of the mean runners' age (for instance for the races in Bulle and Lugano) and while in few others an increase (like for the famous Jungfrau-Marathon, Interlaken ). However in most of the cases changes are too small to claim the presence of trends.

Statistics on Performance VS Age¶

This question has been already investigated in recent studies, on different races across the world. Here are few examples, from 2014(1), 2014(2), 2015, 2016.

All of them found a U-shaped dependence, for both males and females

Let's consider for simplicity the races with largest number of runners (across all editions):

Conclusions¶

On the one hand, the U-dependence observerd in the literature, is present for the most popular swiss events.
On the other hand, it becomes more visible with longer distances (full marathon), while 'fading out' for shorter distance, like 20 and 10 km.

Statistics on Performance VS Weather¶

One of the main study on this topic, from 2007, found correlation between WBGT and decrease of performance, both for male and female runners - we don't have WBGT data, but we could try to compute it following this paper or this website.
(An older study from 1997 found similar negative effects of high ambient temperature on resistance in cyclists)
